 occurs at higher elevations, and the olive tanager occurs further south in the eastern foothills of the Andes in southern Colombia, Peru and Bolivia, with a disjunct population in Central America. Ecology The lemon-spectacled tanager frequents the understorey of lowland wet forests and forest edges, seldom moving above 800 m (2,600 ft) and usually staying below 400 m (1,300 ft). It often occurs in groups of up to four birds, but sometimes forms part of small mixed flocks where it often appears to be the flock leader. It is a noisy species with a loud call, often a rapidly repeated \"treu-treu-treu-treu\". It feeds on insects and some plant matter. Status The International Union for Conservation of Nature has rated this bird as being of \"least concern\". Its population has not been quantified and may be declining slightly, but the bird has a very wide range and does not meet the criteria for being listed in a more-threatened category. References", "shortSummary": "The lemon-spectacled tanager (Chlorothraupis olivacea) is a species of bird in the family Cardinalidae. It is found in Colombia, Ecuador, a…", "locations": ["哥伦比亚", "厄瓜多尔", "巴拿马", "熱帶和亞熱帶濕潤闊葉林"], "habitats": ["山地森林"], "lat": 4.0, "lng": -72.0, "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Chlorothraupis_olivacea_-_Cameron_Eckert_-_633531847.jpeg/960px-Chlorothraupis_olivacea_-_Cameron_Eckert_-_633531847.jpeg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-chlorothraupis", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-chlorothraupis-olivacea", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-chlorothraupis", "species": "taxonomy-species-chlorothraupis-olivacea"}, "expandable": true, "x": -268.02, "y": -326.18, "z": -602.84}, {"id": "taxonomy-genus-chlorothraupis", "name": "Chlorothraupis", "latinName"